Raw dev notes -- Project Hub: Battling the Silent Dead

Okay, so the "Personal Information Hub" project. This thing is basically my attempt to build a central brain for my digital life – pulling in data from various APIs, processing it, and eventually, I want it to automate some mundane tasks and give me a unified view of things. Think personal dashboard meets automation engine. It's been a fun, sometimes frustrating, journey of trying to glue together disparate services and make them play nice.

This past week or so has been less about new features and more about making the damn thing *actually stay alive*. I've been wrestling with some really insidious stability issues.

First up, I finally nailed down a bug where the core processing service would just... hang. Not crash, not throw an error, just stop doing anything useful. My initial thought was it was related to webhooks stalling, but it turned out the problem was deeper. If one of the *external* APIs it relies on became unreachable, the service itself would get stuck in a weird limbo state. It wasn't gracefully handling the external API being down, which meant my internal service was effectively dead, even though it *looked* like it was running. So, I put in a fix to make sure it properly detects when its external dependencies are unreachable and restarts itself. A bit blunt, but effective for now.

But the real beast was the "silent-dead" problem. I use NSSM to run the core service as a Windows service on my home server. The problem was, sometimes NSSM would report the service as "running," but it was actually completely frozen, not processing anything, not responding to anything. It was like a zombie process – technically alive, but brain-dead. This was infuriating because standard monitoring wouldn't catch it. To combat this, I had to build a separate "host-watchdog" process. This watchdog now sends a regular heartbeat to the main service, and the main service, in turn, has logic to detect if *it itself* has gone silent. If it realizes it hasn't sent a heartbeat in a while, or if the watchdog doesn't get a response, it triggers a self-restart. It feels a bit like building a second brain just to monitor the first brain, but it's been surprisingly effective. It's a proper self-healing mechanism now, which feels pretty cool.

And finally, because I'm trying to be a responsible developer (even for my own stuff), I spent some time documenting the migration process. I added ordered runbooks for both Windows and Linux environments. This is less glamorous than coding, but super important. If I ever need to move this thing to a new server, or rebuild it from scratch, I won't be staring at a blank screen wondering how I set everything up. It's a step towards making this project truly maintainable long-term.

Honestly, this whole experience has been a huge lesson in resilience and operational thinking. It's one thing to write code that *works*, it's another thing entirely to write code that *stays working* in the face of network hiccups, external API failures, and its own internal existential crises. There were definitely moments of pulling my hair out, wondering why my perfectly good code was just... sitting there, doing nothing. But the satisfaction of seeing the watchdog kick in and bring the service back to life automatically is immense. It feels like I'm leveling up my "devops-lite" skills, even if it's just for my personal toy project. It's a reminder that building robust systems is about more than just the happy path; it's about anticipating all the ways things can go wrong and planning for them.

Next up: Maybe some actual new features, or perhaps a UI refresh.
